s.  Sound-oriented, will probably work best\twith sound card (PC) or with microphone (Mac).  Should be possibl\tto record your own messages to warn of break    Tool: AudioPort (sound card and software    Available from\tMedia Visio\tTel: +1 (510) 226 256    Platforms: P    Description\tA sound card to plug into your PC parallel port\tIncludes 'At Your Service'    Tool: Computer Health Break (commercial software    Available from\tEscape Ergonomics, In\t1111 W. El Camino Rea\tSuite 10\tMailstop 40\tSunnyvale, C\tTel: +1 (408) 730 841    Platforms: DO    Description\tAimed at preventing RSI, this program warns you to tak\tbreaks after a configurable interval, based on clock time, o\tafter a set number of keystrokes -- whichever is earlier\tIt gives you 3 exercises to do each time, randomly selected fro\ta set of 70.  Exercises are apparently tuned to the type of wor\tyou do - data entry, word processing, information processing\tExercises are illustrated and include quite a lot of text o\thow to do the exercise and on what exactly the exercise does\tCHB includes hypertext information on RSI that you can use\tto learn more about RSI and how to prevent it.  Other informatio\ton non-RSI topics can be plugged into this hypertext viewer\tA full glossary of medical terms and jargon is included\tCHB can be run in a DOS box under Windows, but does not the\twarn you when to take a break; it does not therefore appea\tuseful when used with Windows\tCost: $79.95; quantity discounts, site licenses    Comments\tThe keystroke-counting approach looks good: it seems bette\tto measure the activity that is causing you problems than t\tmeasure clock time or even typing time.  The marketing stuf\tis very good and includes some summaries of research papers\tas well as lots of arguments you can use to get your company\tto pay up for RSI management tools.     Tool: EyerCise (commercial software    Available from\tRAN Enterprise\tOne Woodland Park Dr\tHaverhill, MA  01830, U\tTel: 800-451-4487 (US only    Platforms: Windows (3.0/3.1), OS/2 PM (1.3/2.0) [Not DOS    Description\tAimed at preventing RSI and eye strain, this program warns you to tak\tbreaks after a configurable interval (or at fixed times). Optionall\tdisplays descriptions and pictures of exercises - pictures ar\tanimated and program beeps you to help you do exercises at th\tcorrect rate.  Includes 19 stretches and 4 visual training\texercises, can configure which are included and how many repetition\tyou do - breaks last from 3 to 7 minutes.  Also includes online help\ton workplace ergonomics. \tQuote from their literature\t"EyerCise is a Windows program that breaks up your day with periodi\tsets of stretches and visual training exercises.  The stretches wor\tall parts of your body, relieving tension and helping to preven\tRepetitive Strain Injury.  The visual training exercises will improv\tyour peripheral vision and help to relieve eye strain.  Together thes\thelp you to become more relaxed and productive.\t"The package includes the book _Computers & Visual Stress_ by Edward C\tGodnig, O.D. and John S. Hacunda, which describes the ergonomic setu\tfor a computer workstation and provides procedures and exercises t\tpromote healthy and efficient computer use.\\tCost: $69.95 including shipping and handling, quantity discount\tfor resellers.  Free demo ($5 outside US)    Comments\tI have a copy of this, and it works as advertised: I would sa\tit is better for RSI prevention than RSI management, because i\tdoes not allow breaks at periods less than 30 minutes.  Also, i\tinterrupts you based on clock time rather than typing time, whic\tis not so helpful unless you use the keyboard all day.  Worked OK o\tWindows 3.0 though it did occasionally crash with a UAE - not sur\twhy. Also refused to work with the space bar on one PC, and ha\tone window without window controls.  Very usable though, and does no\trequire any sound hardware    Tool: Lifeguard (commercial software    Available from\tVisionary 